'''Asociación Mutual Social y Deportiva Atlético de Rafaela''' ({{IPA-es|asosjaˈsjon muˈtwal soˈsjal i depoɾˈtiβa aˈtletiko ðe rafaˈela|local}}; usually known simply as '''Atlético de Rafaela''') is an [[Argentina|Argentine]] [[sports club]] from the city of [[Rafaela]], in [[Santa Fe Province]]. The club is mostly known for its professional [[association football|football]] team, which currently plays in [[Primera B Nacional]], the second division of the [[Argentine football league system]].

Apart from football, other sports and activities practised at the institution are [[basketball]], [[chess]], [[field hockey]], [[artistic gymnastics]], [[paddle tennis]], [[roller skating]], [[skeet shooting]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[tennis]] and [[volleyball]].<ref>[http://atleticorafaela.com.ar/contenidos/deportes-amateur/ Deportes amateur] on A. Rafaela website, 28 Sep 2018</ref>

==History==
[[File:Asociaci%C3%B3n_Mutual_Social_y_Deportiva_Atl%C3%A9tico_de_Rafaela.jpg|thumb|left|Atlético Rafaela team of 2012]]
Under the name "Club Atlético Argentino de Rafaela", the club was founded in the city of Rafaela, [[Santa Fe Province]] in 1907. In 1915 the name was changed to "Club Atlético de Rafaela". The Monumental de Barrio Alberdi concrete stadium was erected in 1951.

The club was turned into a non-profit organization in 1988, and renamed ''Asociación Mutual Social y Deportiva Atlético de Rafaela'' ("Social and Sport Association Rafaela Athletic"). Only a year later Rafaela reached the second division after defeating [[Atlético Ledesma]] by 3–0 with goals scored by López (20 ST and 40ST) and Poelman (35ST).<ref>[http://www.lacremaesdeprimera.com.ar/Ascenso_de_1989.htm 1989's Promotion.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201102223/http://www.lacremaesdeprimera.com.ar/Ascenso_de_1989.htm |date=February 1, 2015 }}</ref>

Atlético de Rafaela played 14 years in the second division until the team won the [[Apertura]] 2002 and the [[Clausura]] 2003 to finally reach [[Primera División Argentina|first division]]. After losing the ''[[2003-2004 in Argentine football#"Promoción" Playoff|promoción]]'' against [[Huracán de Tres Arroyos]], Atlético de Rafaela was relegated to the second division again.

The following season Atlético lost its chance to return to the first division, after losing the ''[[2003-2004 in Argentine football#"Promoción" Playoff|promoción]]'', against [[Argentinos Juniors]].

In 2009 Rafaela earned another chance to return to the Primera División via a [[Primera División Argentina 2008–09#Relegation.2Fpromotion playoffs|playoff]] against [[Gimnasia y Esgrima de La Plata]]. After winning the first final 3–0, Rafaela lost the second match by the same score (0–3), and had to stay in the second division once again.

Atlético de Rafaela fans are referred as ''Cremosos'' or ''Celestes'', as well as the group of people that follows the team everywhere is known as ''La Barra de los Trapos'' .

The institution has also an [[Autódromo Ciudad de Rafaela|important car racing circuit]] since 1919, which hosts many competitions including [[Turismo Carretera]] (since 1941) and [[TC 2000]] (since 1983).

The 21st of May 2011, after defeating [[Atlético Tucumán]] by 2–0 with goals scored by [[Oscar Carniello|Carniello]] and [[Alexis Castro (footballer, born 1984)|Aldana]], they earned a spot back on the [[Argentine Primera División|first division]] for the 2011–12 season.<ref>[http://www.ole.com.ar/atletico-rafaela/triunfo-propio-campeon_0_485351627.html "An appropriate triumph from a champ", Diario Olé.]</ref>

