{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Chiswick Park Cricket Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Chiswick]], [[London]] | establishment = 1886 | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year2 = 1887 | club2 = [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] | year1 = 1886 | club1 = [[Charles Thornton (cricketer)|CI Thornton's XI]] | date = 2 September | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/414.html Ground profile }}
'''Chiswick Park Cricket Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Chiswick]], [[London]] (formerly [[Middlesex]]). The first recorded match on the ground was in 1886, when Chiswick Park played the [[Parsees cricket team|Parsees]] during [[Parsees cricket team in England in 1886|their tour of England]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/414_misc.html Other matches played on Chiswick Park]</ref>
The first [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match held on the ground came in 1886 when [[Charles Thornton (cricketer)|CI Thornton's XI]] played the touring [[Australia national cricket team|Australians]]. The second and final first-class match held at the ground came in 1887 when [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] played [[Oxford University Cricket Club|Oxford University]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/414_f.html First-Class Matches played on Chiswick Park Cricket Ground]</ref>
The final recorded match held on the ground came in 1888 when the Gentlemen of West Middlesex played the Parsees during [[Parsees cricket team in England in 1888|their tour of England]]. The ground was located to the north of the [[Hounslow Loop Line]] and was surrounded to the west by Grove Park Terrace, to the north by Fauconberg Road and to the west by Sutton Court Road. Following the [[Second World War]], the ground was built over, with a primary school and apartments built on it.
==References== {{reflist}}
==External links== *[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/414.html Chiswick Park Cricket Ground] on CricketArchive *[http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/ground/56912.html Chiswick Park Cricket Ground] on [[Cricinfo]]
{{coord|51.4846|-0.2714|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}
[[Category:Defunct cricket grounds in England]] [[Category:Cricket grounds in London]] [[Category:Sport in the London Borough of Hounslow]] [[Category:Defunct sports venues in London]] [[Category:Sports venues completed in 1886]] [[Category:Chiswick]]
{{England-cricket-ground-stub}} {{London-sports-venue-stub}}

[[File:Fans_on_field_at_RFK_Stadium_on_September_30,_1971.png|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Fans on the field at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Stadium]] on September 30, 1971, resulted in the [[Washington Senators (1961–71)|Washington Senators]] forfeiting the game to the [[New York Yankees]].]]
In rare cases, [[baseball]] games are [[forfeit (sport)|forfeited]], usually when a team is no longer able to play. In the event of forfeiture, the score is recorded as 9–0, as stated in rule 2.00 of the [[Major League Baseball]] Rules Book. The 9–0 score equates to the number of innings in a regulation game. Actual game statistics are recorded as they stand at the time of the forfeit; the game is recorded as a loss in the standings for the forfeiting team and a win for the other team, even if the forfeiting team is ahead at that point. 

Although not uncommon in baseball's early days, forfeits are now rare. There have been only five forfeits in Major League Baseball since 1954; the last forfeit was in 1995, and prior to that, 1979.  Since 1914, there has only been one incident where a team deliberately made a decision to forfeit a game, by the [[1977 Baltimore Orioles season|1977 Baltimore Orioles]].

Sports with seven-inning games, such as high school baseball or softball, generally award a rule-based score of 7–0. The same is true for [[Little League Baseball]], per Rule 2.00, under the definition of "Forfeit", there is one run allocated per inning, so for Minors and Majors divisions, that would be score of 6–0, and for Intermediate and above divisions, that would be a score of 7–0. In [[college baseball]], the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] has the authority to retroactively forfeit games if the winning team is found to have violated NCAA rules. This can also happen for [[Little League World Series]] games, and occurred following the [[1992 Little League World Series|1992]] and [[2014 Little League World Series|2014]] events.

== MLB forfeits before 1970 ==
Forfeits were more common in the early days of [[Major League Baseball]]. In 1871, six games were forfeited in two months. There was at least one forfeit almost every year from 1882 until 1909. 1884 saw forfeits in the double digits, many because one team failed to appear for a game or refused to continue playing. Game 2 of the [[1885 World Series]] was forfeited when St. Louis pulled its team from the field to protest the umpiring. There were five forfeits in the National League in [[1886 in baseball|1886]]. The high rate of forfeits slowed after 1910, with one forfeit every few years. Game 7 of the [[1934 World Series]] was in jeopardy of being forfeited when [[Detroit Tigers]] fans began showering the outfield with debris after [[St. Louis Cardinals]] left fielder [[Joe Medwick]] slid hard into Tigers third baseman [[Marv Owen]]; however, a potential black eye to the Series was averted when Commissioner [[Kenesaw Mountain Landis]] ordered both Medwick and Owen replaced in the one-sided game.

In games that were played before the advent of stadium lighting (or had an enforced curfew), forfeits were also sometimes declared as a result of a team's stalling tactics. A baseball game is not official until 5 innings have been completed, or {{frac|4|1|2}} innings if the home team is winning.  Consequently, a team that was behind by a considerable number of runs before the end of the fifth inning might deliberately slow down the game, in the hopes that darkness or the curfew would come before the game was declared official. Note, however, that deliberate attempts to slow down play for this reason are subject to a forfeiture being declared.  The last such incident took place in 1954. On July 18, the visiting [[Philadelphia Phillies]] were leading the hometown [[St. Louis Cardinals]] 8–1 in the fifth inning of the second game of a doubleheader. With darkness approaching and the game not yet official, Cardinals manager [[Eddie Stanky]] brought in three new pitchers in the inning.  Umpire [[Babe Pinelli]], citing an unnecessary delay of the game on the part of the Cardinals, forfeited the game to the Phillies.

Forfeits have become extremely rare in recent years. The advent of night baseball has eliminated the use of stalling tactics to beat the sunset. No major league city has been regularly subject to a general curfew in recent decades. In the sort of extraordinary circumstances that would warrant a temporary curfew in a city scheduled to host MLB games (such as the [[1989 San Francisco earthquake|1989 World Series earthquake]]), it is extremely unlikely Major League Baseball would allow the game(s) to be played. In such cases, MLB has invariably rescheduled the game(s), moved the game(s) to the opponents' stadium or a neutral venue and/or ordered the game(s) played [[behind closed doors (sport)|without spectators]] (the latter scenario [[2015 White Sox–Orioles crowdless game|first occurring as a consequence]] of the [[2015 Baltimore protests]]).

Of the five forfeits that have occurred in the expansion era of baseball (post-1960), all but one have been the result of fans disrupting the game to a point where the stadium staff cannot control them, at which point the home team is forced to forfeit.

== MLB forfeits since 1970==
* [[Washington Senators (1961–71)|Washington Senators]]' final game at [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|RFK Stadium]]: On September 30, 1971, the home team led the [[New York Yankees]] by 7–5 with two outs in the top of the ninth inning. Senators fans were angered by the team's impending move to [[Dallas]]&ndash;[[Fort Worth]], where the Senators were to become the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] in [[1972 in baseball|1972]]. Forgetting one out was left in the game, they [[pitch invasion|stormed the field]] and vandalized the stadium.<ref>{{cite book|last=Leventhal|first=Josh|title=Take Me Out to the Ballpark: An Illustrated Tour of Baseball Parks Past and Present|publisher=Black Dog & Leventhal Publishers|year=2000|location=[[New York City]]|isbn=1-57912-112-8}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Yankees Win Finale on a Forfeit, 9-0|newspaper=The New York Times|page=49|date=October 1, 1971|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1971/10/01/79155298.pdf}}</ref> With no prospect of order being restored (the [[security guard]]s had simply left early during the game which resulted in many fans walking in without paying), the umpires forfeited the game to the Yankees.<ref name="sensforfeit">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/history/rfk/articles/baseball.htm|last=McPherson|first=Myra|last2=Huth|first2=Tom|title=Rowdy Fans Hand Senators Final Loss|publisher=The Washington Post|date=October 1, 1971}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last2=Shannon|first2=Bill|last=Kalinsky|first=George|title=The Ballparks|location=New York|publisher=Hawthorn Books, Inc|year=1975|authorlink=George Kalinsky}}</ref>
* [[Ten Cent Beer Night]]: A promotion held by the [[Cleveland Indians]] on June 4, 1974, backfired when intoxicated Cleveland fans ran  onto the field and attacked [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] [[outfielder]] [[Jeff Burroughs]] with the score tied 5–5 in the ninth inning. This led to a riot in which the drunken and rowdy fans—armed with an array of debris including chunks of the stadium seating—[[wikt:brawl|brawl]]ed with players from both teams as well as with umpires. The umpires forfeited the game to Texas.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Riot by Indians' Fans in 9th Forfeits Game to Rangers|newspaper=The New York Times|pages=35|date=June 5, 1974|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1974/06/05/79627644.pdf}}</ref>
* During the September 15, 1977, game between the [[Baltimore Orioles]] and [[Toronto Blue Jays]] at [[Exhibition Stadium]], a light rain had been falling, and the grounds crew placed a tarpaulin over the two mounds in the Blue Jays' bullpen, which was in foul territory, outside the left field foul line.  Before the start of the bottom of the fifth inning (with the Blue Jays leading 4–0), Orioles manager [[Earl Weaver]] came out of the dugout and claimed to umpire [[Marty Springstead]] that the tarp endangered his players by exposing them to the risk that they could slip or trip on it when entering the bullpen to catch a fly ball. Weaver removed his team from the field and said that they would not return until the tarp was removed. Springstead ordered the tarp removed from the mound that was closest to fair territory, but refused to order the removal of the tarp from the other mound and told Weaver that he could play the game under protest. After arguing with Springstead for nearly twenty minutes, Weaver returned to the dugout. Springstead then waited five minutes (the period of time specified by the rule book) for the Orioles to retake the field. When they did not do so, he ordered the game forfeited to the Blue Jays.<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Orioles Lose by a Forfeit In Bull-Pen Mound Dispute|page=93|date=September 16, 1977|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1977/09/16/91215328.pdf}}</ref> This is the only time since 1914 that a major-league baseball team has deliberately forfeited a game.{{Fact|date=April 2018}}
* [[Disco Demolition Night]]:  On July 12, 1979, the [[Chicago White Sox]] held a game in which Chicago radio personality [[Steve Dahl]] came onto the field to blow up a box full of [[disco]] records between games of a [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]] with the [[Detroit Tigers]]. After the box was blown up, rowdy and intoxicated fans who had packed [[Comiskey Park]] beyond capacity  stormed the field, engaged in various acts of vandalism and theft, and did not leave the field until the arrival of Chicago police in full riot gear. The field was so badly torn up that the umpires decided the second game could not be played. [[American League]] President [[Lee MacPhail]] later forfeited the second game to [[Detroit]].<ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Anti-Disco Rally Halts White Sox|page=A16|date=July 13, 1979|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1979/07/13/284376162.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|newspaper=The Washington Post|page=C2|date=July 14, 1979}}</ref>
* On August 10, 1995, the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] gave out baseballs to paying customers as they entered the [[Dodger Stadium]] gates for a game against the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. However, fans interrupted the game in the seventh inning when they threw these baseballs onto the field. In the bottom of the ninth inning, the Cardinals were leading the game 2–1. The first batter, [[Raúl Mondesí]], was called out on strikes and then ejected by home plate umpire [[Jim Quick]] for arguing, as was Dodger manager [[Tommy Lasorda]] moments later. Dodger fans, fueled by a series of close calls again threw their souvenir baseballs onto the field. The Cardinals left the field due to safety concerns and the field was cleaned up so play could resume. However, when the Cardinals returned to the field, at least one ball sailed out of the center field bleachers and the umpires immediately forfeited the game to [[St. Louis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/08/11/sports/baseball-rowdy-fans-cause-dodgers-to-forfeit-game.html?scp=1&sq=dodgers&st=nyt|title=Rowdy Fans Cause Dodgers to Forfeit Game|work=The New York Times| date= August 11, 1995|page=B9|accessdate=2010-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-08-11/sports/sp-34067_1_baseball-fans|title=Three Strikes and Dodgers Forfeit: Baseball Game is called after fans throw balls on the field with one out in the ninth. Nomo overshadowed|last=Baker|first=Chris|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=1995-08-11}}</ref> As a result of this incident, Major League Baseball decreed that for any future promotional giveaways of baseballs or any other throwable object, the items would be given out as fans exited the stadium.{{Fact|date=April 2018}}

