{{Infobox stadium | name = Stoney Lane | nickname = | image = | caption = | fullname = | location = [[West Bromwich]], England | coordinates = {{Coord|52.5237|-1.9902|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | broke_ground = | built = | opened = 1885 | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | surface = Grass | cost = | architect = | capacity = | record_attendance = 20,977 | dimensions = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] }}
'''Stoney Lane''' was a [[association football|football]] ground in [[West Bromwich]], England. It was the home ground of [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] from 1885 until 1900.
==History== West Bromwich Albion moved to Stoney Lane in 1885 from their [[West Bromwich Albion F.C. former grounds|Four Acres]] ground in 1885. A 600-seat grandstand was built on the southern touchline, with open wooden stands on each side of the grandstand. Banking was raised on the northern touchline.<ref name=UD>Paul Smith & Shirley Smith (2005) ''The Ultimate Directory of English & Scottish Football League Grounds Second Edition 1888–2005'', Yore Publications, p126, {{ISBN|0954783042}}</ref>
In 1888 West Bromwich Albion were founder members of [[the Football League]], and the first league match was played at Stoney Lane on 29 September 1888, with West Brom beating [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] 4–3 with 2,100 in attendance. The ground's record league attendance of 19,700 was set on 5 January 1895 when West Brom lost 5–4 to [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]],<ref name=UD/> whilst the overall record attendance of 20,977 was set in March 1895, for Albion's 1–0 victory over local rivals [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in the [[FA Cup]] third round.<ref>Matthews, Tony; Mackenzie, Colin (1987) ''Albion! A Complete Record of West Bromwich Albion 1879–1987'', Breedon Books, p233–234 {{ISBN|0-907969-23-2}}</ref>
At the end of the [[1899–1900 Football League|1899–1900 season]] the club moved to [[the Hawthorns]], taking the wooden grandstand with them. The final league match was played at Stoney Lane on 16 April 1900, with West Brom beating [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] 8–0. Stoney Lane remained in use as a training ground for some time, and was later known as the Fairground because of its use by visiting fairs. It was used to build a housing estate in the 1980s.<ref name=UD/> The area which was covered by the pitch is now a road named Albion Field Drive.
==Related links== [http://www.stoneylane.net/about Stoney Lane Records] - UK-based jazz/world record label named after the former West Bromwich Albion home. The label's catalogue numbers all relate to significant years or honours for West Brom.<ref>Official wba.co.uk website - http://www.wba.co.uk/news/article/bowlers-delivery-west-bromwich-albion-ruel-fox-2402349.aspx</ref>
